    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$59.4B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$12.8B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$25.68</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">23.2%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">-${Math.abs(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Debt (Excl. Investments)</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF (Insurance Nuances)</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model. However, applying a standard DCF to a property and casualty (P&C) insurer requires understanding some crucial nuances.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Chubb generated <strong>$12.8 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. In the insurance industry, cash flow metrics can be volatile year-to-year depending on catastrophic loss payouts and investment portfolio restructuring, but $12.8B represents strong actual cash generation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>4% per year</strong> for 5 years. A massive, globally diversified insurer like Chubb typically grows near or slightly above GDP, primarily driven by premium rate increases and steady returns on their massive investment float. 4% is a historically sustainable rate.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>3% forever</strong>. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate). This steady-state rate ensures we don't assume indefinite hyper-growth for an established insurer.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>9.5%</strong>. This represents our required rate of return. Given Chubb's lower beta (typically around 0.65-0.70) and exceptionally strong balance sheet, their cost of equity is arguably lower than a standard tech company. We use 9.5% as a conservative hurdle rate above the 10Y Treasury (4.18%).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add Net Cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>For an insurer, we only subtract actual corporate debt ($17.6B) and add corporate cash/equivalents ($2.47B). <strong>Crucially, we do NOT treat Chubb's $168B investment portfolio as "free cash."</strong> Those investments back their insurance reserves ($122B+ in claims reserves). We only value the operating cash flows that the float and underwriting generate. Enterprise Value + Net Cash (-$15.2B) = Equity Value. Divide by diluted shares outstanding (402M).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">4%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Chubb grew revenue consistently (15.4% in 2023, 12.1% in 2024, 6.5% in 2025). But high premium growth eventually normalizes. A 4% cash flow growth rate acknowledges stable underwriting and modest ongoing yield improvements on their float without assuming unsustainable hard market conditions forever.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">9.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. Equity risk premium: ~5.5%. Chubb is an incredibly stable underwriter, meaning it requires a slightly lower return premium than the broader market. 9.5% is a very fair hurdle rate to discount future cash from an A++ rated insurer.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">3%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is ~3%. We assume Chubb simply tracks broader global economic expansion in perpetuity. Insurance premiums fundamentally track asset values and economic activity, making 3% a textbook terminal rate.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (FY2025)</td>
          <td>${fcf2025.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year} ({2025 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × 1.03)</td>
          <td>${Math.round(fcfYear6).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Terminal Value (FCF₆ ÷ (9.5% − 3%))</td>
          <td>${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
