  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses for an insurance company.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Prolonged Hard Market:</strong> If commercial P&C pricing stays elevated longer than expected, premium growth and underwriting margins will easily beat our 4% FCF growth assumption.</li>
    <li><strong>Higher Interest Rates:</strong> Insurers invest their float in bonds. If rates stay higher for longer, investment income compounds rapidly as the $168B portfolio rolls over into higher-yielding assets.</li>
    <li><strong>Share buybacks:</strong> Chubb consistently buys back shares. Fewer shares = higher per-share value over time. Our model assumes a static share count.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Catastrophe Losses (CATs):</strong> A year with historically bad hurricanes, wildfires, or earthquakes can wipe out a full year of FCF. The DCF assumes a "normalized" catastrophe load.</li>
    <li><strong>Reserve Development:</strong> If inflation causes older claims (like liability or workers' comp) to cost more than expected, Chubb will have to strengthen reserves, which directly hits cash and earnings.</li>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Cuts:</strong> A rapid drop in bond yields would eventually compress investment income margins as the portfolio matures.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of Dividend Discount Model (DDM) for an insurer?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While DDM is historically popular for financials, Chubb generates significantly more Free Cash Flow than it pays out in dividends. A pure DDM would severely undervalue the business by ignoring the cash retained to grow book value or execute buybacks.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why aren't you counting their $168B investment portfolio as cash?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">That money doesn't fully belong to shareholders—yet. It is "float." It backs the $122B in claims reserves owed to policyholders. Shareholders only have a claim on the investment income that float generates, and whatever is left over after all claims are paid. The cash flows generated by the portfolio are already captured in the FCF metric.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is a 9.5% discount rate used?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Chubb is generally viewed as one of the highest-quality, most disciplined underwriters in the world. Their earnings stream is much more stable than an average S&P 500 company, justifying a lower risk premium (discount rate).</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

